author: Michael Steadman
---

Preheat the oven to 200°C. Trim the @carrot{2} and @parsnip{1}, then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons. Quarter the @pear{1} lengthways (No need to peel), carefully cut out the core and cut each quarter in half lengthways. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a garlic press). Chop the @salad potatoes{350%g} into 2cm pieces (no need to peel). Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Pick the leaves from the @rosemary{1/2} and finely chop (discard the stalks).

Put the carrot, parsnip, pear, garlic and potatoes onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle over the @honey{15%g}, add a splash of @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Sprinkle on the chopped rosemary then use your hands to coat everything thoroughly. Arrange the veggies in a single layer then pop in the oven on the middle shelf and roast until tender and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}, turning halfway through.

Once the veggies have been in the oven for 5 minutes, place the @caramelised onion sausages{4} on a separate baking tray and roast on the top shelf of your oven for ~{20-25%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

> IMPORTANT: The sausages are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of @oil{} in a #small saucepan{} on a medium-high heat. When hot, add the shallot and cook until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the @water{50%ml}, @reduced fat creme fraiche{112.5%g} and @chicken stock powder{1%tsp}. Simmer, whilst stirring frequently until the sauce has thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}, then stir the @wholegrain mustard{1%tbsp} into the sauce, bring back to a boil and set aside.

Reheat the sauce gently if necessary. Share the honey-roasted veg between your plates and arrange the sausages on top. Pour over the mustard sauce. Enjoy!